      <hedline>
        <hl1>Clemens, Piazza And a Bad Call</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Fred Polvere letter on umpires' decision not to eject New York Yankee pitcher Roger Clemens for throwing a piece of broken bat toward New York Mets' Mike Piazza (Oct 24 editorial)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Baseball Justice'' (editorial, Oct. 24):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Baseball Justice'' (editorial, Oct. 24):</p>
        <p>You call the umpires' decision not to eject Roger Clemens, the Yankee pitcher, for throwing a piece of broken bat across the path of the Mets' Mike Piazza understandable because they probably ''did not want to disrupt a championship game.'' This overlooks the point of officiating in sports.</p>
        <p>We expect and demand umpires to be blind to all but that which is going on in the field. The importance of a game is not a determining factor as to whether a rule was broken. In fact, it is because the game is so important that umpires must insure that their calls are fair and that the rules are not bent.</p>
        <p>FRED POLVERE  Yonkers, Oct. 24, 2000</p>
      </block>
